{"id":40337,"date":"2021-05-27T11:01:44","date_gmt":"2021-05-27T15:01:44","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/jamesclear.vercel.app\/?post_type=3-2-1&#038;p=40337"},"modified":"2022-10-17T16:00:31","modified_gmt":"2022-10-17T20:00:31","slug":"may-27-2021","status":"publish","type":"3-2-1","link":"https:\/\/jamesclear.vercel.app\/3-2-1\/may-27-2021","title":{"rendered":"3-2-1: On dealing with conflict, writing books, and working on the right level"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<h2 id=\"h-3-ideas-from-me\">3 IDEAS FROM ME<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>I.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>&#8220;Convincing someone to change their mind is really the process of convincing someone to change their tribe. If they abandon their beliefs, they run the risk of losing social ties. You can\u2019t expect someone to change their mind if you take away their community too. You have to give them somewhere to go.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Nobody wants their worldview torn apart if loneliness is the outcome.&#8221;<\/p>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-css-opacity\"\/>\n\n\n\n<p>\u200bII.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>&#8220;If you think you can learn a lot from reading books, try writing one.&#8221;<\/p>\n\n\n<div id=\"block_60afb3d3ffb99\" class=\"twitter-share \" data-easygut-id=\"twitter\">\n\t<div><a href=\"https:\/\/ctt.ac\/V4fTX\"><svg width=\"24\" height=\"27\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 27\" fill=\"none\" xmlns=\"http:\/\/www.w3.org\/2000\/svg\">\n<circle cx=\"12\" cy=\"14\" r=\"12\" fill=\"#EDEADE\"\/>\n<path d=\"M16.3613 12.1406C16.791 11.8184 17.1777 11.4316 17.4785 10.9805C17.0918 11.1523 16.6406 11.2812 16.1895 11.3242C16.6621 11.0449 17.0059 10.6152 17.1777 10.0781C16.748 10.3359 16.2539 10.5293 15.7598 10.6367C15.3301 10.1855 14.75 9.92773 14.1055 9.92773C12.8594 9.92773 11.8496 10.9375 11.8496 12.1836C11.8496 12.3555 11.8711 12.5273 11.9141 12.6992C10.0449 12.5918 8.36914 11.6895 7.25195 10.3359C7.05859 10.6582 6.95117 11.0449 6.95117 11.4746C6.95117 12.248 7.33789 12.9355 7.96094 13.3438C7.5957 13.3223 7.23047 13.2363 6.92969 13.0645V13.0859C6.92969 14.1816 7.70312 15.084 8.73438 15.2988C8.5625 15.3418 8.34766 15.3848 8.1543 15.3848C8.00391 15.3848 7.875 15.3633 7.72461 15.3418C8.00391 16.2441 8.8418 16.8887 9.83008 16.9102C9.05664 17.5117 8.08984 17.877 7.03711 17.877C6.84375 17.877 6.67188 17.8555 6.5 17.834C7.48828 18.4785 8.66992 18.8438 9.95898 18.8438C14.1055 18.8438 16.3613 15.4277 16.3613 12.4414C16.3613 12.334 16.3613 12.248 16.3613 12.1406Z\" fill=\"#111111\"\/>\n<\/svg>\n<\/a><\/div>\n\t<div><a href=\"https:\/\/ctt.ac\/V4fTX\">Share this on Twitter<\/a><\/div>\n<\/div>\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-css-opacity\"\/>\n\n\n\n<p>III.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>&#8220;The list of mistakes you can never recover from is very short.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>But you likely realize your life will not be destroyed if your book doesn\u2019t sell or if a potential date turns you down or if your startup goes bust. It\u2019s not the failed outcome that paralyzes us. It\u2019s the possibility of looking stupid, feeling humiliated, or dealing with embarrassment that prevents us from getting started at all.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The first step to being courageous is being willing to look foolish.&#8221;<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-2-quotes-from-others\">2 QUOTES FROM OTHERS<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>I.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>French moralist<strong> Joseph Joubert<\/strong> on dealing with conflict:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>&#8220;Never cut what you can untie.&#8221;<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><em>Source: <\/em><a href=\"https:\/\/www.google.com\/books\/edition\/Some_of_the_Thoughts_of_Joseph_Joubert\/YXEaAAAAYAAJ?hl=en&amp;gbpv=1\"><em>Some of the &#8220;Thoughts&#8221; of Joseph Joubert<\/em><\/a><em><\/em><\/p>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-css-opacity\"\/>\n\n\n\n<p>\u200bII.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Author <strong>Marilynne Robinson <\/strong>on why she writes:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>INTERVIEWER: What led you to start writing essays?<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>ROBINSON: &#8220;To change my own mind. I try to create a new vocabulary or terrain for myself, so that I open out \u2014 I always think of the Dutch claiming land from the sea \u2014 or open up something that would have been closed to me before. That\u2019s the point and the pleasure of it. I continuously scrutinize my own thinking. I write something and think, How do I know that that\u2019s true? If I wrote what I thought I knew from the outset, then I wouldn\u2019t be learning anything new.&#8221;<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><em>Source: <\/em><a href=\"https:\/\/www.amazon.com\/gp\/product\/1847674496\/ref=as_li_qf_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=jamesclearema-20&amp;creative=9325&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;creativeASIN=1847674496&amp;linkId=aeac78a6a10fae7447ede41b36542097\"><em>The Paris Review Interviews: Volume IV<\/em><\/a><\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-1-question-for-you\">1 QUESTION FOR YOU<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Am I working at the right level? Do I need to zoom in or zoom out?<\/p>\n\n\n\n\n\n<p>Until next week,<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>James Clear <br><em>Author of the multi-million-copy bestseller, <\/em><a href=\"https:\/\/atomichabits.com\/\"><em>Atomic Habits<\/em><\/a><em>\u200b <\/em><br><em>Creator of the <\/em><a href=\"https:\/\/jamesclear.vercel.app\/habit-journal\"><em>Habit Journal<\/em><\/a><em>\u200b<\/em><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>p.s. <a href=\"https:\/\/jamesclear.vercel.app\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/10\/editors-note.png\">Editor&#8217;s Note<\/a>.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>3 IDEAS FROM ME I. &#8220;Convincing someone to change their mind is really the process of convincing someone to change their tribe. If they abandon their beliefs, they run the risk of losing social ties. You can\u2019t expect someone to change their mind if you take away their community too. You have to give them [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":40295,"menu_order":0,"template":"","acf":[],"yoast_head":"<!-- This site is optimized with the Yoast SEO Premium plugin v20.5 (Yoast SEO v20.6) - https:\/\/yoast.com\/wordpress\/plugins\/seo\/ -->\n<title>3-2-1: On dealing with conflict, wri